{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}
{{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2014}}
'''Arthur John Burns''' (22 October 1830 – 15 September 1901) was a prominent early settler of [[Otago]], New Zealand, a member of the [[Otago Provincial Council]], a member of the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]] and founder of the [[Mosgiel]] Woollen Company, [[Dunedin]].

==Biography==
{{NZ parlbox header|nolist=true|align=right}}
{{NZ parlbox
 |start      = [[Bruce by-election, April 1865|1865]]
 |end        = 1866
 |term       = 3rd
 |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|Bruce}}
 |party      = Independent politician
}}
{{NZ parlbox
 |start      = {{NZ election link year|1866}}
 |end        = 1870
 |term       = 4th
 |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|Caversham}}
 |party      = Independent politician
}}
{{NZ parlbox break}}
{{NZ parlbox
 |start      = [[New Zealand general election, 1875–76|1875]]<!-- election held on 28 December 1875 -->
 |end        = 1878
 |term       = 6th
 |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|Roslyn}}
 |party      = Independent politician
}}
{{NZ parlbox footer}}
Burns was born in [[Monkton, Ayrshire|Monkton]], [[South Ayrshire]], [[Scotland]]. He was the only son and eldest child of [[Thomas Burns (minister)|Thomas Burns]] and Clementina Grant and the great-nephew of the poet [[Robert Burns]]. He came to Otago with his father in the ''[[Philip Laing]]'' arriving in [[Port Chalmers]] on 15 April 1848.<ref name="NZETC Burns">{{cite book |title=The Cyclopedia of New Zealand : Otago & Southland Provincial Districts |year=1905 |url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-Cyc04Cycl-t1-body1-d2-d6-d2.html#name-427765-mention |author=Cyclopedia Company Limited |accessdate= 8 July 2010 |location=Christchurch |chapter=Ex-Members}}</ref>

He played a prominent part in provincial affairs and was a member of the Provincial Council from 1855 to 1859 and again from 1863 to 1870. On three occasions, he served on the Executive Council of the [[Otago Province]].{{sfn|Scholefield|1950|p=217}} He was also a member of the New Zealand House of Representatives on three occasions; [[Bruce (New Zealand electorate)|Bruce]] 1865–1866, [[Caversham (New Zealand electorate)|Caversham]] 1866–1870 when he resigned, and [[Roslyn (New Zealand electorate)|Roslyn]] 1875–1878 when he resigned.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=187}} He vigorously opposed the abolition of the [[Provinces of New Zealand|provinces]] in 1876.

On 6 April 1861 he married Sarah Scott Dickson, with whom he had 11 children.

He founded the Mosgiel Woollen Company in 1871 in an area on the western outskirts of Dunedin. Burns named the town Mosgiel after his great-uncle Robert Burns's Mossgiel farm in [[Ayrshire]], [[Scotland]].<ref>[http://www.rampantscotland.com/placenames/placename_dunedin.htm Scottish Place Names - Dunedin, New Zealand]</ref> He imported skilled labour and specialised equipment from [[Great Britain]] to begin large scale [[clothmaking]] in 1873.<ref>[http://www.buykiwimade.govt.nz/wehavegotitmade/Timeline.aspx Manufacturing in New Zealand Timeline] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324134458/http://www.buykiwimade.govt.nz/wehavegotitmade/Timeline.aspx |date=24 March 2008 }}</ref> This mill formed the backbone of the Mosgiel economy for decades.

Burns died on 15 September 1901 and is memorialised in the names of two schools - Arthur Burns School in Mosgiel and the Arthur Burns Early Learning Centre. Arthur Burns School in Mosgiel has since been amalgamated with two other primary schools in the region.

